<br>
Example:<br>
I have an &quot;addictive personality&quot; (the phrase itself means nothing, but most people understand what it means). After high school I stayed up til 3 am watching TV most nights avoiding my college homework. Then I slept through classes the next day. I dropped out of school and took tech training courses (WARNING!!!: DO NOT TAKE TECH TRAINING COURSES) thinking I could get by on what the training would teach me. I started playing Magic:the Gathering during this time. I played Magic EVERY chance I could, including during work hours (I was in construction and had a vehicle). I stayed out til 4 am on weekends on average. Usually those nights were for poker after Magic. I started school again and moved and started playing EQ. Then I played EQ every single night for 2 years just about. I quit EQ, and started watching TV until 3 am again. TV is WAY better than it used to be by the way. Then the spark hit me to start playing Magic occasionally again, just to check it out. Now I am playing 2-3 nights a week, til 12am. <br>
<br>
Granted I am more responsible and mature than I used to be, so I allocate a great deal less time to the escapes than I used to. But just last night I was at a Magic shop (or a nerdery as I like to call it), and my brother calls and asks if I wanna see a movie with him and have dinner. I had nothing to do at the moment and I haven't seen him for 2 weeks, nor will I get to for 2 more weeks, and I told him I've already eaten and to call me back with the time and that I'd meet him there. Well, he really didnt give a @#%$ about the movie he just wanted to hang out, so he said you just play your Magic and went without me. <br>
<br>
I think I'll regret that for a long time. I should have said &quot;sure, be right there&quot;, but the escape is difficult to run away from. <br>
<br>
It all has to do with the fact that the video games, TV, card games, gambling, drinking, collecting porn, collecting music, buying things constantly (usually focusing on one material genre. Your car, clothes, furniture, stereo, etc), masturbation, skateboarding, and so on [i]replace real life and responsibility with an activity that requires neither of these, but still gives you the same feeling of having completed real life and holding real responsibility[/i]. <br>
<br>
People blame the activity, when in fact it is the personality avoiding real life that is the issue. <br>
